## Update: March 9, 2026 — The Crisis Enters Its Second Week

*The following section was added six days after original publication. The analysis above reflects conditions and understanding as of March 3. It is preserved intact as a record of the positional view at publication. What follows documents how quickly that view was overtaken by events.*

---

Six days is a long time in a war. The framework built above — chokepoint activated by insurance withdrawal, price spike of 22%, Asian importers scrambling — now reads as a description of the opening hours. The week since has produced escalations that exceeded most analyst scenarios at publication.

### The Oil Price Rewrite

On March 3, Brent crude was trading at approximately $84 per barrel — a 22% spike that felt dramatic at the time. By the evening of March 8, Brent briefly touched **$126 per barrel** before closing around $99. WTI posted its biggest weekly gain in recorded history at 35.6%. The chart in Part B showing a $84 peak on March 3 understates the current situation by roughly 50%.

