The disruption to global supply is being described as the largest in recorded history — roughly twice the scale of the Suez Crisis of 1956–57, according to Rapidan Energy Group. Neil Atkinson, former head of oil at the International Energy Agency, said the effective closure of the Strait of Hormuz was something energy markets had never seen before, warning of a "potentially game-changing and unprecedented energy crisis."

### The Strait Has Not Reopened

The most consequential update is the most straightforward: the strait remains effectively closed. Trump's announcement on March 3 that the US Development Finance Corporation would provide political risk insurance and guarantee safe transit briefly calmed markets — but did not reopen the waterway. Tanker traffic that had dropped to near zero has not recovered materially.

The consequences have cascaded into production. Iraq and Kuwait have already begun to shut in output. Analysts warn that the UAE and Saudi Arabia may also be vulnerable if the closure persists for another two to three weeks. Gulf Arab producers are not reducing output by choice — they are running out of storage capacity because crude is accumulating with nowhere to go. The G7 finance ministers convened a virtual meeting on March 9 and issued a joint statement indicating readiness to release emergency petroleum reserves.

### Escalations Not Priced In at Publication

Several developments since March 3 have materially altered the picture.

**A new Supreme Leader — and an immediate target.** Mojtaba Khamenei, the second son of the slain Supreme Leader, was elected by the Assembly of Experts on March 8 to replace his father. The IDF immediately warned that any successor to Khamenei would be treated as a target, introducing new uncertainty about whether the leadership transition accelerates de-escalation or merely extends the conflict under different management.

**Ceasefire formally rejected.** Iranian Foreign Minister Abbas Araghchi rejected all ceasefire calls on NBC News' *Meet the Press*, stating Iran needs to continue fighting for the sake of its people and its security. His argument: the US and Israel had already shattered the ceasefire that ended last year's twelve-day war, making a new short-term arrangement non-credible. Iran has not asked for a ceasefire — Araghchi noted Iran did not ask for one last time either.

**Hezbollah's second front opens.** On March 2, Hezbollah began firing rockets and missiles on Israel in retaliation for the killing of Khamenei. Israel launched air strikes on southern Lebanon and south Beirut, followed by a ground incursion by the 91st Division. As of March 9, nearly 400 people have been killed since Israel opened its campaign in Lebanon — and Israel stated that Lebanon has now made more attacks against them than Iran has over the past week. The conflict has formally expanded beyond the Iran–Israel bilateral.

**Iran's own oil infrastructure struck.** On March 7, Israel struck Iranian oil infrastructure for the first time since the start of the war, targeting the Shahran oil depot in Tehran. This marks a qualitative escalation: Iran shifts from a supply-corridor risk (blocking other countries' exports) to a supply-volume risk (losing its own roughly 4.6 million barrels per day of crude and condensate production capacity). The symmetry is now established — both sides are targeting oil assets.

**Russia's intelligence support.** NBC News reported that Russia is providing Iran with intelligence on the location of US forces in the Middle East, including information that could help Iran locate American warships. The great-power dimension of the crisis has expanded in a direction not anticipated in the original analysis.

### The Duration Question Reassessed

The original article framed duration as the critical variable. Entering week two, the scenario distribution has shifted materially toward the longer tail.

ExxonMobil chief economist Tyler Goodspeed put the analytical problem directly: "When I think of the probability distribution of possible outcomes here, it seems to me there are many more scenarios, and more probable scenarios, in which the strait remains effectively closed harder for longer than there are scenarios in which normal traffic resumes." Rystad Energy estimated Brent could reach $135 per barrel if current conditions persist for four months; above $110 for two months.

The forward curve tells a different story: oil futures contracts for delivery in 2027 and 2028 are trading in the high $60s, indicating that markets still price a return to pre-war conditions. The backwardation — current barrels trading at roughly $14 premium over next-month futures — is extreme, and it signals that the physical shortage is real even as traders expect eventual resolution.

### What Changes for the Framework — and for Alberta

The four-force framework in Part G remains structurally valid. The directional argument for Alberta's TMX advantage has strengthened. But the magnitude assumptions need revision.

At publication, the scenario range in Part F was built around a $84–$90 Brent shock with resolution in weeks. The market is now pricing $108+ with meaningful probability attached to $135 and a duration measured in months. Every variable in the oil-shock simulator — inflation transmission, food security exposure, emerging market fiscal stress — should be re-run with those updated parameters.

One new variable has entered the picture: Trump is reportedly considering reducing oil sanctions on Russia to ease crude prices. If enacted, this would partially offset the Gulf supply disruption with increased Russian flows via the shadow fleet infrastructure described in *Contested Ground* — a politically complex move that reintroduces the sanction-reshuffle dynamic the original article documented.

Alberta's position: the window is open and materially larger than anticipated. WTI at $94 on March 9, compared with approximately $60 before the strikes, represents a roughly $34/barrel premium that significantly exceeds any credible estimate of break-even costs for incremental oil sands output. The question is no longer whether the window exists — it is whether existing TMX throughput can be expanded quickly enough to capture the premium before the conflict resolves, and whether the current price level is sufficient to unlock capital for any remaining expansion capacity.

The original article closed by observing that the world built its energy system as though the Strait of Hormuz were infinite. One week later, that assumption is not merely being tested — it is being priced.

